node.text: Not sure I’ve made a better peanut butter cookie than these from the updated Tartine book. Bringing back all the childhood memories ✨ #cookies #Tartine #baking #peanutbutter
More 60% whole grain goodness with Red Fife, spelt, rye (again). The easy boule baked this morning will be ready for a family lunch. Happy weekend, all.

Keeping an eye on my sourdough levain 👀 This was a typical build for me but with some flour changes: 75% all purpose, 25% whole rye, 115% hydration, 100% mature starter kept at 78-80F for 3 hours or so. Used right after it fell in the video (when you start seeing streaks at the sides). #sourdough #starter #levain
Yesterday’s hearty spelt, rye, and whole wheat loaves. Just love the look and feel of that dough fully proofed. These were scaled at 900g each and are in a 14” long basket. Proof was 14 hours at 42F.

A little behind the scenes this morning baking my spelt, rye, and wheat recipe up at my website. A few changes: increased the whole grains by 10% and used @kingarthurflour whole white wheat in place of hard red wheat. Upped the hydration a bit (see stories!), lower FDT to 76F, and pushed bulk to 4 hours — a wet and active dough. Nice to have a new flock of hearty loaves in the house again to feed the ravenous lot (me included). #baking #bread #sourdough #theperfectloaf
Always hypnotic, these sourdough cinnamon rolls. 🌀More dough mixing later today, looking forward to working in some whole grains back into rotation.
Whipping up a batch of cream cheese icing for some sourdough cinnamon rolls this week.  I’m not making them till later but that doesn’t mean I can’t start snacking now 👹

The procrastinator in me thanks myself for mixing a batch of canelé batter a few days ago (when I posted the cut video) — now I have some ready for Valentine’s Day and QC gives them a ✅ #valentines #canele

Having fun with a mostly-white loaf (as seen in my Stories)— lofty like a ☁️ . Did a longer 4.25 hr bulk at a cooler temp (FDT: 76F). Shaped the bubbly dough tight and retarded overnight at a cool 40F. Pretty darn tasty even with the 90% white flour/10% ww ratio. Maybe the soft texture making up for the lack of whole grains 🙂

Another weekend, another satisfying focaccia. Made simply with rosemary and coarse sea salt sprinkled on top. Added a little extra oil as the kids wanted it “soft and crispy” — they don’t have to twist my arm 🙂

Crunch. More canelé using the recipe at my website because, well, I can’t get enough of em. Got the bottom nice and flat this bake — sometimes you’ll get a little dip where the batter/wax pools ever so slightly. Not a problem IMO, they still taste just as great 👍🏼
Wonderful flavors in this winter inspired sourdough with nuts, dried cranberry, and sage. Definitely my next recipe post. Smells somehow like Christmas in my kitchen. So good!
Hello, beautiful dough. A long sourdough bâtard with dried cranberries and a few other spices — in testing — ready for the oven🔥
In keeping with the round theme: more boules! Definitely not my most common shape — by a long measure — but appropriate for some doughs, and for a change of pace.

🍞 Just posted a new schedule and recipe to my website (link in profile) with a sample schedule for baking sourdough during a busy weekday. A super simple recipe aimed to eliminate any excuses for baking during the week 😉 Swipe for the after shot 👉🏼.

Another simple boule this morning baked in a Dutch oven. A straightforward mix of white flour and some whole wheat (80/20) — something to get us through the week.  #baking #sourdough #bread #lunch #keepitsimple
Some flour, water, starter, and time. Playing with some flour I had in the pantry, a random mix of this and that. 🙂 #fermentation #baking #sourdough #bread #onthetable

Today’s lunch: red lentil hummus with scallions/Aleppo/evoo, my fresh rye/spelt/wheat sourdough toast, and avocado. Recipe from @cannellevanille new book, which is beautifully shot, written, and styled. And the hummus is mighty good 👌🏼

The outside and inside of a couple of the loaves baked yesterday: rye/spelt/whole wheat. Such a deep, wonderful flavor. Might have been able to push the water a bit higher, but happy with the fermentation in these. #baking #bread #sourdough

From easy score to oven to cooling. Baked my spelt/rye/whole wheat recipe (at my website in profile) this morning as the light just came in through the windows and the chill creeped into the room—even the glowing oven couldn’t contest. #baking #bread #sourdough #morningroutine #theperfectloaf

Playing with an off-shoot of my lievito madre: kept this 200g madre, 200g flour, 100g water in the fridge for a little over two weeks bound tight (the Italian method for maintaining a sourdough starter, particularly when used for panettone). Over this time, it formed a solid layer on the outside with soft interior — obviously left far too long between refreshments. Smelled like sharp vinegar. Chances are it would come back after several days of timely refreshments, but there’s no need for me since this was a bit of a fun test. I did this method for a week last month and it worked just fine, I’d likely not go too much more than this without the expectation of a long cycle to bring it back to “life.” #testing #sourdough #baking #panettone #fermentation #lievitomadre
Frothy and ready to go. #sourdough #starter #bread #baking #ritual

The magic of rising bread strictly confined to a covered tin. Golden pain de mie from my website, always a hit with the kiddos (and me, to be honest). Perhaps the best bread for butter and jelly, perhaps. #sourdough #baking #bread #theperfectloaf

Fig and walnut comfort bread today as the snow comes down in a gentle, but never ending, assault on anything and everything outside. Baking and snow seem to go together just as well as this bread will with some soft cheese cheese. #baking #sourdough #bread #onthetable #kingarthurflour

More fun with doughs today. This one with fig and walnuts, always a winning combination. I usually toast my walnuts before mixing into a dough, didn’t this time — we’ll see how the flavor changes. #baking #sourdough #dough #bread
